# Appendix A. Total Variation Estimates along Probability Flow 

In this section, we prove the following general theorem for continuity equations, which is independent of the particular choice of $U_{t}, \widehat{U}_{t}$ (equivalently, $V_{T-t}, \widehat{V}_{T-t}$ ) in (11).
Theorem A.1. Fix any $0<\tau<T$. Let $\widehat{q}_{t}(x), q_{t}(x) \in C^{1}\left([\tau, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d}\right) \cap L^{1}\left([\tau, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d}\right)$ solve the following two continuity equations on $\mathbb{R}^{d}$ respectively,

$$
\partial_{t} q_{t}=\nabla \cdot\left(U_{t} q_{t}\right), \quad \partial_{t} \widehat{q}_{t}=\nabla \cdot\left(\widehat{U}_{t} \widehat{q}_{t}\right)
$$

We also assume that for $t \in[\tau, T], U_{t}, \widehat{U}_{t}$ are locally Lipschitz on $\mathbb{R}^{d}$. Then, if we denote $\delta_{t}(x):=$ $\widehat{U}_{t}(x)-U_{t}(x), \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t}(x):=\widehat{q}_{t}(x)-q_{t}(x)$, we have that,

$$
\left|\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\widehat{\varepsilon}_{\tau}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x-\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\widehat{\varepsilon}_{T}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x\right| \leq \int_{\tau}^{T} E(t) \mathrm{d} t, \quad \text { with } E(t):=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\left(\nabla \cdot\left(q_{t} \delta_{t}\right)\right)(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x
$$

First Proof. Fix $\tau>0$. For $t>0$, we define the total variation between $\widehat{q}_{t}(x)$ and $q_{t}(x)$ as

$$
f(t):=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x
$$

We use $x_{t}:=T_{t}(x)$ to denote the solution of the ODE (also called the characteristic line)

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} T_{t}(x)=-\widehat{U}_{\tau+t}\left(T_{t}(x)\right)
$$

with the initial data $x_{0}=T_{0}(x)=x$. We notice that, by change of variables (we can do this because $\widehat{U}_{t}$ is locally Lipschitz on $\mathbb{R}^{d}$, so, $T_{t}$ is a diffeomorphism of $\left.\mathbb{R}^{d}\right)$,

$$
f(t)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\left(x_{t}\right)\right| J T_{t}(x) \mathrm{d} x
$$

where $\left.J T_{t}(x)=\left|\operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)\right|\right.$. A direct computation shows that

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}(x)=\left(\nabla \cdot\left(\widehat{U}_{t+\tau} \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\right)\right)(x)+\left(\nabla \cdot\left(q_{t+\tau} \delta_{t+\tau}\right)\right)(x)
$$

Hence,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t}\left[\widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\left(x_{t}\right)\right] & =\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\right)\left(x_{t}\right)+\left[\nabla \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\left(x_{t}\right) \cdot \frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} x_{t}\right] \\
& =\left(\nabla \cdot\left(\widehat{U}_{t+\tau} \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\right)\right)\left(x_{t}\right)+\left(\nabla \cdot\left(q_{t+\tau} \delta_{t+\tau}\right)\right)\left(x_{t}\right)+\left[\nabla \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\left(x_{t}\right) \cdot\left(-\widehat{U}_{\tau+t}\left(x_{t}\right)\right)\right] \\
& =\left(\nabla \cdot \widehat{U}_{t+\tau}\right)\left(x_{t}\right) \cdot \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\left(x_{t}\right)+\left(\nabla \cdot\left(q_{t+\tau} \delta_{t+\tau}\right)\right)\left(x_{t}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Jacobi's formula gives that

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)=\operatorname{trace}\left(\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \nabla T_{t}(x)\right) \cdot\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)^{-1}\right) \cdot \operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)
$$

We also notice that

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \nabla T_{t}(x)=\nabla \frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} T_{t}(x)=-\nabla\left(\widehat{U}_{\tau+t}\left(T_{t}(x)\right)\right)=-\left(\nabla \widehat{U}_{\tau+t}\right)\left(T_{t}(x)\right) \cdot \nabla T_{t}(x)
$$

So,

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)=-\operatorname{trace}\left(\left(\nabla \widehat{U}_{\tau+t}\right)\left(T_{t}(x)\right)\right) \cdot \operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)=-\left(\nabla \cdot \widehat{U}_{\tau+t}\right)\left(T_{t}(x)\right) \cdot \operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)
$$

Also, by (21), we have that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} f(t)\right| & =\left|\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \frac{\mathrm{~d}}{\mathrm{~d} t}\right| \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\left(x_{t}\right) \operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)\left|\mathrm{d} x\right| \leq \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\frac{\mathrm{~d}}{\mathrm{~d} t}\right| \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\left(x_{t}\right) \operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)\left|\mid \mathrm{d} x\right. \\
& =\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\frac{\mathrm{~d}}{\mathrm{~d} t}\left[\widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\left(x_{t}\right) \operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)\right]\right| \mathrm{d} x
\end{aligned}
$$

Hence,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} f(t)\right| \leq & \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\left[\left(\nabla \cdot \widehat{U}_{t+\tau}\right)\left(x_{t}\right) \cdot \widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\left(x_{t}\right)+\left(\nabla \cdot\left(q_{t+\tau} \delta_{t+\tau}\right)\right)\left(x_{t}\right)\right] \cdot \operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)\right. \\
& \left.+\widehat{\varepsilon}_{t+\tau}\left(x_{t}\right) \cdot\left(-\left(\nabla \cdot \widehat{U}_{\tau+t}\right)\left(T_{t}(x)\right)\right) \cdot \operatorname{det}\left(\nabla T_{t}(x)\right)\right) \mathrm{d} x \\
= & \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\left(\nabla \cdot\left(q_{t+\tau} \delta_{t+\tau}\right)\right)\left(x_{t}\right)\right| \cdot J T_{t}(x) \mathrm{d} x \\
= & \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\left(\nabla \cdot\left(q_{t+\tau} \delta_{t+\tau}\right)\right)(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x=E(t+\tau)
\end{aligned}
$$

where the second last equality is by change of variables again. Hence, for any $t^{\prime}>0$,

$$
f(0) \leq \int_{0}^{t^{\prime}} E(t+\tau) \mathrm{d} t+f\left(t^{\prime}\right)
$$

One can also use the characteristic line method starting from $t=T$ to $t=\tau$, and then obtain an inverse inequality. Hence, we finish the proof of the theorem.
Remark A.2. Notice that in this first proof, we exchange the order of integrals and derivatives. We can do this in our problem setting (11), because by Assumption 3.1, $\mu_{*}$ is compactly supported, so $q_{t}(x)$ always has an exponential tail as $\|x\| \rightarrow+\infty . \widehat{q}_{t}(x)$ also has such a property by our Lemma B.6.

Indeed, one can prove the following more general theorem with reasonable assumptions, essentially verbatim, by the same method.

Theorem A.3. Fix any $0<\tau<T$. Let $p_{t}(x) \in C^{1}\left([\tau, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d}\right) \cap L^{1}\left([\tau, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d}\right)$ solve the following continuity equation on $\mathbb{R}^{d}$ with $h_{t}(x) \in L^{1}\left([\tau, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d}\right)$,

$$
\partial_{t} p_{t}(x)=\left(\nabla \cdot\left(Z_{t} p_{t}\right)\right)(x)+h_{t}(x)
$$

We also assume that for $t \in[\tau, T], Z_{t}$ is locally Lipschitz on $\mathbb{R}^{d}$. Then, for almost all $t \in[\tau, T]$, we have that,

$$
\left|\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\right| p_{t}(x)| \mathrm{d} x| \leq \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|h_{t}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x
$$

Hence,

$$
\left|\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\right| p_{\tau}(x)| \mathrm{d} x-\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|p_{T}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x\left|\leq \int_{\tau}^{T} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\right| h_{t}(x) \mid \mathrm{d} x
$$

Remark A.4. We will prove a Gagliardo-Nirenberg interpolation inequality with dimension free constants in Lemma C.1. With this inequality, if one can know that $\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\partial_{\alpha}^{2} p_{\tau}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x$ is bounded for some $i \in \llbracket 1, d \rrbracket$, then one can use Lemma C. 1 to see that $\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\partial_{i} p_{\tau}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x$ is also small if $\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|p_{\tau}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x$ is small. Similar arguments work for higher order derivatives of $p_{\tau}(x)$. Moreover, if we can conclude that the $W^{k, 1}\left(\mathbb{R}^{d}\right)$-norms of $p_{\tau}(x)$ is small, where $W^{k, 1}$ denotes the Sobolev space, we can use Sobolev inequalities to conclude that the $W^{k-1, r}\left(\mathbb{R}^{d}\right)$-norms of $p_{\tau}(x)$ for a corresponding $r>1$ is also mall. In particular, we can conclude that the $L^{r}\left(\mathbb{R}^{d}\right)$-norm of $p_{\tau}(x)$ is small.

Before we give the second proof of Theorem A. 1 and Theorem A.3, we need to explain our intuition a little bit. With those notations in Theore A.3, we notice that for

$$
g(t):=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|p_{t}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x
$$

we have that

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} g(t)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \operatorname{sign}\left(p_{t}(x)\right) \frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} p_{t}(x) \mathrm{d} x=\int_{\left\{p_{t} \geq 0\right\}} \frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} p_{t}(x) \mathrm{d} x-\int_{\left\{p_{t}<0\right\}} \frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} p_{t}(x) \mathrm{d} x
$$

If the boundary $\partial\left\{p_{t} \geq 0\right\}$ consists of $(d-1)$-dimensional piecewise smooth submanifolds (or at least rectifiable sets), then by the divergence theorem, we know that

$$
\int_{\left\{p_{t} \geq 0\right\}}\left(\nabla \cdot\left(Z_{t} p_{t}\right)\right)(x) \mathrm{d} x=\int_{\partial\left\{p_{t} \geq 0\right\}} \mathbf{n}(x) \cdot\left(Z_{t} p_{t}\right)(x) d \mathcal{H}^{d-1}(x)=0
$$

where $\mathbf{n}(x)$ is the unit outer normal vector and $\mathcal{H}^{d-1}(\cdot)$ is the $(d-1)$-dimensional surface measure. Similarly,

$$
\int_{\left\{p_{t}<0\right\}}\left(\nabla \cdot\left(Z_{t} p_{t}\right)\right)(x) \mathrm{d} x=0
$$

So,

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} g(t)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \operatorname{sign}\left(p_{t}(x)\right) h_{t}(x) \mathrm{d} x, \text { and }\left|\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} g(t)\right| \leq \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|h_{t}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x
$$

However, in general, we cannot know whether the boundary set $\partial\left\{p_{t} \geq 0\right\}$ is always of $(d-1)$ dimension. For an arbitrarily given smooth function, its zero level set can also be arbitrarily strange and does not necessarily need to be of $(d-1)$-dimension.

The following second proof of Theorem A. 3 is inspired by [3] and the communication with Professor Guido De Philippis. We also assume that $\left(\left\|Z_{t}(x)\right\| \cdot\left|p_{t}(x)\right|\right) \in L^{1}\left(\mathbb{R}^{d} \times[\tau, T]\right)$.

Second Proof. Let $a>0$. We let $\beta_{a}(s)=\sqrt{a^{2}+s^{2}}$ be a function on $\mathbb{R}$ which approximates the function $|s|$ as $a \rightarrow 0^{+}$. Then, the function $p_{a, t}(x):=\beta_{a}\left(p_{t}(x)\right)$ on $\mathbb{R}^{d}$ solves the equation

$$
\begin{aligned}
\partial_{t} p_{a, t}(x) & =\left(\left(\nabla \cdot Z_{t}\right)(x)\right) p_{t}(x) \beta_{a}^{\prime}\left(p_{t}(x)\right)+Z_{t}(x) \cdot \nabla p_{a, t}(x)+h_{t}(x) \beta_{a}^{\prime}\left(p_{t}(x)\right) \\
& =\nabla \cdot\left(Z_{t}(x) p_{a, t}(x)\right)+\left(\left(\nabla \cdot Z_{t}\right)(x)\right)\left[p_{t}(x) \beta_{a}^{\prime}\left(p_{t}(x)\right)-p_{a, t}(x)\right]+h_{t}(x) \beta_{a}^{\prime}\left(p_{t}(x)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

For any $R>0$, consider the integral of the above equation on the ball $B_{R}:=B_{R}(0) \subset \mathbb{R}^{d}$, we have that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \int_{B_{R}} p_{a, t}(x) \mathrm{d} x= & \int_{\partial B_{R}}\left(Z_{t}(x) p_{a, t}(x)\right) \cdot \frac{x}{\|x\|_{2}} d \mathcal{H}^{d-1}(x)+\int_{B_{R}}\left(\left(\nabla \cdot Z_{t}\right)(x)\right)\left[p_{t}(x) \beta_{a}^{\prime}\left(p_{t}(x)\right)-p_{a, t}(x)\right] \mathrm{d} x \\
& +\int_{B_{R}} h_{t}(x) \beta_{a}^{\prime}\left(p_{t}(x)\right) \mathrm{d} x
\end{aligned}
$$

and then for any $t^{\prime}, t^{\prime \prime} \in[\tau, T]$ and $t^{\prime}>t^{\prime \prime}$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|\int_{B_{R}} p_{a, t^{\prime \prime}}(x) \mathrm{d} x-\int_{B_{R}} p_{a, t^{\prime}}(x) \mathrm{d} x\right|= & \left|\int_{t^{\prime \prime}}^{t^{\prime}} \int_{\partial B_{R}}\left(Z_{t}(x) p_{a, t}(x)\right) \cdot \frac{x}{\|x\|_{2}} d \mathcal{H}^{d-1}(x) \mathrm{d} t\right. \\
& +\int_{t^{\prime \prime}}^{t^{\prime}} \int_{B_{R}}\left(\left(\nabla \cdot Z_{t}\right)(x)\right)\left[p_{t}(x) \beta_{a}^{\prime}\left(p_{t}(x)\right)-p_{a, t}(x)\right] \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} t \\
& \left.+\int_{t^{\prime \prime}}^{t^{\prime}} \int_{B_{R}} h_{t}(x) \beta_{a}^{\prime}\left(p_{t}(x)\right) \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} t\right|
\end{aligned}
$$

Notice that $\left|\beta_{a}^{\prime}(s)\right|=\frac{|s|}{\sqrt{a^{2}+s^{2}}} \leq 1,\left|p_{t}(x) \beta_{a}^{\prime}\left(p_{t}(x)\right)-p_{a, t}(x)\right|=\frac{a^{2}}{\sqrt{a^{2}+p_{t}(x)^{2}}} \leq 1$, and for any given $x \in B_{R}, \lim _{a \rightarrow 0^{+}} \frac{a^{2}}{\sqrt{a^{2}+p_{t}(x)^{2}}}=0$. By the dominated convergence theorem, we can let $a \rightarrow 0^{+}$on both sides and obtain that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|\int_{B_{R}}\right| p_{t^{\prime \prime}}(x)\left|\mathrm{d} x-\int_{B_{R}}\right| p_{t^{\prime}}(x)\left|\mathrm{d} x\right|= & \left|\int_{t^{\prime \prime}}^{t^{\prime}} \int_{\partial B_{R}}\left(Z_{t}(x)\right) p_{t}(x)\right|) \cdot \frac{x}{\|x\|_{2}} d \mathcal{H}^{d-1}(x) \mathrm{d} t \\
& +\int_{t^{\prime \prime}}^{t^{\prime}} \int_{B_{R}}\left(\left(\nabla \cdot Z_{t}\right)(x)\right) \cdot 0 \mathrm{~d} x \mathrm{~d} t \\
& \left.+\int_{t^{\prime \prime}}^{t^{\prime}} \int_{B_{R}} h_{t}(x) \operatorname{sign}\left(p_{t}(x)\right) \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} t\right| \\
\leq & \int_{t^{\prime \prime}}^{t^{\prime}} \int_{\partial B_{R}}\left\|Z_{t}(x)\right\|_{2} \cdot\left|p_{t}(x)\right| d \mathcal{H}^{d-1}(x) \mathrm{d} t \\
& +\int_{t^{\prime \prime}}^{t^{\prime}} \int_{B_{R}}\left|h_{t}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} t
\end{aligned}
$$

Because we assumed that $\left(\left\|Z_{t}(x)\right\|_{2} \cdot\left|p_{t}(x)\right|\right) \in L^{1}\left(\mathbb{R}^{d} \times[\tau, T]\right)$, we can choose a sequence $\left\{R_{j}\right\}$ with $R_{j} \rightarrow+\infty$, such that the first term on the right hand side goes to 0 . So, by the monotone convergence theorem, after passing $R_{j} \rightarrow+\infty$, we obtain that for any $t^{\prime}, t^{\prime \prime} \in[\tau, T]$ and $t^{\prime}>t^{\prime \prime}$,

$$
\left|\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\right| p_{t^{\prime \prime}}(x)\left|\mathrm{d} x-\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\right| p_{t^{\prime}}(x)\left|\mathrm{d} x\right| \leq \int_{t^{\prime \prime}}^{t^{\prime}} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|h_{t}(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} t
$$

# Appendix B. Preliminary Estimates on Forward and Backward Density 

In this section, $U_{t}, \widetilde{U}_{t}$ are defined as in (11). Under Assumption 3.1, we take $\lambda_{t}=e^{-t}$ and $\sigma_{t}=\sqrt{1-\lambda_{t}^{2}}(t>0)$, and we also assume that

$$
q_{t}(y):=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \frac{1}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y-x\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}{ }^{2}}} \cdot \mu_{*}\left(\frac{x}{\lambda_{t}}\right) \frac{1}{\lambda_{t}{ }^{d}} \mathrm{~d} x
$$

which satisfies the first-order PDE: $\partial_{t} q_{t}=\nabla \cdot\left(U_{t} q_{t}\right)$ for $U_{t}=x+\nabla \log q_{t}(x)$. We remark that although we use the notation $\mu_{*}\left(x / \lambda_{t}^{d}\right) / \lambda_{t}^{d}$ in the definition (23) of $q_{t}$, because the data distribution $\mu_{*}$ can be supported on a submanifold $K_{*}$, or more general lower dimensional rectifiable sets, the meaning of it is actually the push-forward measure defined by $\left(\lambda_{t}\right)_{\#} \mu_{*}(A):=\mu_{*}\left(\lambda_{t}^{-1} A\right)$ for any measurable set $A \subset \mathbb{R}^{d}$. So, the rescaling factor $\lambda_{t}^{d}$ is actually $\lambda_{t}^{k}$ for $k \leq d$ when $K_{*}$ is a $k$-dimensional submanifold in $\mathbb{R}^{d}$. But this notation doesn't affect our computations. As readers will see, the only property we will use is that in the integrand of (23), $x / \lambda_{t} \in K_{*}$ and hence $\|x\|_{\infty} \leq \lambda_{t} D$.
Example B.1. When $\mu_{*}$ is the delta mass at a point $y_{0} \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$, then for $t>0$,

$$
q_{t}(y)=\frac{1}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y-y_{0}\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}{ }^{2}}}, \quad \nabla q_{t}(y)=-\frac{y-y_{0}}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} q_{t}(y), \quad \nabla^{2} \log q_{t}(y)=-\frac{1}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \cdot \mathbb{I}_{d}
$$

We notice that as $t \rightarrow 0^{+}$, the derivatives of $\log q_{t}(y)$ blow up.
Example B.2. When $\mu_{*}$ is the unit 2 -sphere $\mathbb{S}^{2} \subset \mathbb{R}^{3} \subset \mathbb{R}^{d}$, if we write $y=\left(y^{\prime}, y^{\prime \prime}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{3} \times \mathbb{R}^{d-3}$ and $y^{\prime}=\left(y_{1}, y_{2}, y_{3}\right)$, a direct computation shows that

$$
q_{t}(y)=\frac{2 \pi}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}+\lambda_{t}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}{ }^{2}}} \cdot \frac{\sigma_{t}^{2}}{\lambda_{t}\left\|y^{\prime}\right\|_{2}} \cdot\left(e^{\frac{\lambda_{t}\left\|y^{\prime}\right\|_{2}}{\sigma_{t}^{2}}}-e^{-\frac{\lambda_{t}\left\|y^{\prime}\right\|_{2}}{\sigma_{t}^{2}}}\right)
$$

The derivatives of $\log q_{t}(y)$ also blow up as $t \rightarrow 0^{+}$by a direct computation.
In general, we have the following estimates for space directions derivatives of $q_{t}(y)$ and $\log q_{t}(y)$. An interesting fact is that the upper bound in the statement of Lemma B. 3 is independent of $y \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ if the derivatives are of order two or higher.

Lemma B.3. For any $p \geq 3$, any $y \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ and any $t>0$,

$$
\left\|\nabla^{p} \log q_{t}(y)\right\|_{\infty} \leq\left(4 p!\right) \frac{\lambda_{t}{ }^{p} D^{p}}{\sigma_{t}{ }^{2 p}}
$$

Also, for any $i, j$,

$$
\left|\partial_{y_{i}} \log q_{t}(y)\right| \leq \frac{\left|y_{i}\right|+\lambda_{t} D}{\sigma_{t}^{2}}, \text { and }\left|\partial_{y_{i} y_{j}}^{2} \log q_{t}(y)\right| \leq \frac{\delta_{i j}}{\sigma_{t}^{2}}+2 \frac{\lambda_{t}^{2} D^{2}}{\sigma_{t}^{4}}
$$

Proof. For simplicity, for a function $f(x)$ defined on $\mathbb{R}^{d}$, we denote

$$
\langle f(x)\rangle:=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} f(x) \mathrm{d}\left(\lambda_{t}\right)_{\#} \mu_{*}(x)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} f(x) \mu_{*}\left(\frac{x}{\lambda_{t}}\right) \frac{1}{\lambda_{t}{ }^{d}} \mathrm{~d} x
$$

Hence, $q_{t}(y)=\left\langle\frac{1}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y-x\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}{ }^{2}}}\right\rangle$. For simplicity, we discuss the derivatives of the logarithm of the $y$-function $h(y):=\left\langle e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle$, where $a \in \mathbb{R}$ is a constant. We will choose $a=-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}}$ finally, and the difference between $\|y-x\|_{2}^{2}$ and $\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}=\|-y-x\|_{2}^{2}$ doesn't influence the $\|\cdot\|_{\infty}$-norms of derivatives.

We first compute the first and second derivatives of $\log h(y)$. We notice that

$$
\partial_{i} h(y)=2 a\left\langle\left(y_{i}+x_{i}\right) e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle=2 a y_{i} h(y)+2 a\left\langle x_{i} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle
$$

So,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\partial_{i j}^{2} h(y) & =2 a \delta_{i j} h(y)+2 a y_{j}\left(2 a y_{i} h(y)+2 a\left\langle x_{i} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle\right)+4 a^{2}\left\langle\left(x_{i}+y_{i}\right) x_{j} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \\
& =2 a \delta_{i j} h(y)+4 a^{2} y_{i} y_{j} h(y)+4 a^{2} y_{i}\left\langle\left(x_{j} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle+4 a^{2} y_{j}\left\langle x_{i} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle+4 a^{2}\left\langle x_{i} x_{j} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle\right.
\end{aligned}
$$

Hence,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\partial_{i j}^{2} \log h(y) & =\frac{\partial_{i j}^{2} h(y) h(y)-\partial_{i} h(y) \partial_{j} h(y)}{h(y)^{2}} \\
& =2 a \delta_{i j}+4 a^{2} \frac{\left\langle x_{i} x_{j} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle h(y)-\left\langle x_{i} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle\left\langle x_{j} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle}{h(y)^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Before we compute higher order derivatives of $\log h(y)$, we first illustrate how we obtain an upper bound for $\partial_{i j}^{2} \log h(y)$. Notice that in the definition of $\langle f(x)\rangle$ in (25), because $\mu_{*}$ has a compact support $K_{*}$, the $x$ in the integrand satisfies that $x \in \lambda_{t} K_{*}$. Hence, in the integrand of (25), $\|x\|_{\infty} \leq \lambda_{t} D$ by Assumption 3.1. So, $\left|\left\langle x_{i} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle\right| \leq \lambda_{t} D h(y),\left|\left\langle x_{i} x_{j} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle\right| \leq \lambda_{t}^{2} D^{2} h(y)$. So, $\left|\partial_{i j}^{2} \log h(y)\right| \leq 2 a \delta_{i j}+8 a^{2} \lambda_{t}^{2} D^{2}$.

Then, we compute $\nabla^{p} \log q_{t}(y)$ for $p \geq 3$. Before we start, we remark that an important observation is that, in (28), there is no polynomial term of $y_{i}, y_{j}$ like we have seen in (26) and (27). We will then use induction to get the formula of $\nabla^{p} \log h(y)$ with $p \geq 2$. Assume that for an $m \in \mathbb{Z}_{+}$, and for any multi-index $\alpha$ with $|\alpha|=m$, the derivative $\partial_{y}^{\alpha} \log h(y)$ has a form

$$
\partial_{y}^{\alpha} \log h(y)=(2 a)^{m} \frac{P_{\alpha}(y)}{h(y)^{m}}
$$

where $P_{\alpha}(y)$ is the $\mathbb{R}$-linear combination of at most $4(m-1)!-2$ terms, where each term has a form

$$
\pm\left\langle x^{\beta_{1}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdot\left\langle x^{\beta_{2}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdots\left\langle x^{\beta_{m}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle
$$

and each $\beta_{i}$ is a multi-index and $\left|\beta_{1}\right|+\left|\beta_{2}\right|+\ldots+\left|\beta_{m}\right|=m$. This assumption is satisfied when $m=2$ according to the explicit form of $\partial_{i j}^{2} \log h(y)$ shown in (28), excluding the term $2 a \delta_{i j}$. This $2 a \delta_{i j}$ term in (28) can be safely excluded for the induction because its derivative is 0 . Then,

$$
\partial_{y_{1}} \partial_{y}^{\alpha} \log h(y)=(2 a)^{m} \partial_{y_{1}} \frac{P_{\alpha}(y)}{h(y)^{m}}=(2 a)^{m+1} \cdot \frac{1}{2 a} \partial_{y_{1}} P_{\alpha}(y) h(y)-m P_{\alpha}(y)\left\langle\left(y_{1}+x_{1}\right) e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle}{h(y)^{m+1}}
$$

We notice that

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{1}{2 a} \partial_{y_{1}}\left(\left\langle x^{\beta_{1}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdot\left\langle x^{\beta_{2}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdots\left\langle x^{\beta_{m}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle\right) \\
& =m y_{1}\left\langle x^{\beta_{1}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdot\left\langle x^{\beta_{2}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdots\left\langle x^{\beta_{m}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \\
& \quad+\left\langle x_{1} x^{\beta_{1}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdot\left\langle x^{\beta_{2}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdots\left\langle x^{\beta_{m}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \\
& \quad+\left\langle x^{\beta_{1}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdot\left\langle x_{1} x^{\beta_{2}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdots\left\langle x^{\beta_{m}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \\
& \quad+\ldots+\left\langle x^{\beta_{1}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdot\left\langle x^{\beta_{2}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdots\left\langle x_{1} x^{\beta_{m}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle
\end{aligned}
$$

Hence, $\frac{1}{2 a} \partial_{y_{1}} P_{\alpha}(y)$ is of the form $m y_{1} P_{\alpha}(y)+Q_{\alpha}(y)$, where $Q_{\alpha}(y)$ is the summation of at most $4(m-1)!-2$ terms without $y_{1}$ showing in the polynomial terms. We notice that those $y_{1}$ terms in

the numerator of (29) will then cancel, and the remaining terms all look like

$$
\pm\left\langle x^{\beta_{1}^{\prime}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdot\left\langle x^{\beta_{2}^{\prime}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle \cdots\left\langle x^{\beta_{m+1}^{\prime}} e^{a\|y+x\|_{2}^{2}}\right\rangle
$$

where each $\beta_{i}^{\prime}$ is a multi-index and $\left|\beta_{1}^{\prime}\right|+\left|\beta_{2}^{\prime}\right|+\ldots+\left|\beta_{m+1}^{\prime}\right|=m+1$. The number of them is at most $m(4(m-1)!-2)+m=4 m!-m \leq 4 m!-2$ when $m \geq 2$. We then conclude the proof of Lemma B.3.

The following lemma describes the situation when $t>0$ is very large. We remark that one can also use Lemma 9 in [7] to obtain a similar result as Lemma B.4.

Lemma B.4. Let $q_{t}(y)$ be defined in (23), and let

$$
g(y):=\frac{1}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{q}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2}}
$$

Then, we have that for $t>0$,

$$
\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|q_{t}(y)-g(y)\right| \mathrm{d} y \leq \frac{2 d\left(1-\sigma_{t}\right)}{\sigma_{t}^{d+3}}+\lambda_{t} \sqrt{d} D \frac{4+\lambda_{t} \sqrt{d} D}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \cdot e^{\frac{\lambda_{t}^{2} d D^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}}}
$$

In particular, there exists a universal constant $C_{u}>0$, such that

$$
\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|q_{t}(y)-g(y)\right| \mathrm{d} y \leq C_{u} e^{-t} \sqrt{d} D
$$

which goes to 0 exponentially as $t \rightarrow+\infty$.
Proof. Because one can write

$$
q_{t}(y)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \frac{1}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{q}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\left\|y-\lambda_{t} \varphi\right\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}}} d \mu_{*}(x)
$$

and $\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} d \mu_{*}(x)=1$, we see that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|q_{t}(y)-g(y)\right| \mathrm{d} y & =\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \mid \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \frac{1}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\left\|y-\lambda_{t} \varphi\right\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}}}-\frac{1}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2}} d \mu_{*}(x) \mid \mathrm{d} y \\
& \leq \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \frac{1}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\left\|y-\lambda_{t} \varphi\right\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}}}-\frac{1}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2}} \mathrm{~d} y d \mu_{*}(x)
\end{aligned}
$$

We denote $y=\left(y_{1}, y^{\prime}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$, and we define the function

$$
f(y, r):=\left|\frac{1}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\left|\sigma_{1}-\lambda_{t} r\right|^{2}+\left\|y^{\prime}\right\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}}}-\frac{1}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2}}\right|
$$

By the rotation symmetry, we see that the right hand side of (32) equals to

$$
\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} f\left(y,\|x\|_{2}\right) \mathrm{d} y d \mu_{*}(x)
$$

Let's first see what is $\left|\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d} r} f(y, r)\right|$ for $r \leq \sqrt{d} D$. A direct computation shows that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} r} f(y, r)\right| & =\frac{\lambda_{t}}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot \frac{\left|y_{1}-\lambda_{t} r\right|}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\left|y_{1}-\lambda_{t} r\right|^{2}+\left\|y^{\prime}\right\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}}} \\
& \leq \frac{\lambda_{t}}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot \frac{\left|y_{1}\right|+\lambda_{t} \sqrt{d} D}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \cdot e^{-\frac{1}{2} \frac{\left|y_{1}\right|^{2}-\lambda_{t}^{2} d D^{2}+\left\|y^{\prime}\right\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}}}
\end{aligned}
$$

So, (33) is bounded by

$$
\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} f(y, 0) \mathrm{d} y d \mu_{*}(x)+\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \frac{\lambda_{t}\|x\|_{2}}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot \frac{\left|y_{1}\right|+\lambda_{t} \sqrt{d} D}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\frac{1}{2}\left|y_{1}\right|^{2}-\lambda_{t}^{2} d D^{2}+\left\|y^{\prime}\right\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}{ }^{2}}} \mathrm{~d} y d \mu_{*}(x)
$$

The second term in (34) is bounded by

$$
\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \frac{\lambda_{t} \sqrt{d} D}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot \frac{\left|y_{1}\right|+\lambda_{t} \sqrt{d} D}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\frac{1}{2}\left|y_{1}\right|^{2}-\lambda_{t}^{2} d D^{2}+\left\|y^{\prime}\right\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}{ }^{2}}} \mathrm{~d} y \leq \lambda_{t} \sqrt{d} D \frac{4+\lambda_{t} \sqrt{d} D}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \cdot e^{\frac{\lambda_{t}^{2} d D^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}{ }^{2}}}
$$

which goes to 0 exponentially as $t \rightarrow+\infty$ because $\lambda_{t}=e^{-t}$ and $\sigma_{t}^{2}=1-\lambda_{t}^{2}$.
The first term in (34) is

$$
\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\frac{1}{\left(\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{t}\right)^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}{ }^{d}}}-\frac{1}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2}}\right| \mathrm{d} y
$$

because $\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} d \mu_{*}(x)=1$. We define the function

$$
h(y, \alpha)=\left|\frac{1}{(\sqrt{2 \pi} \alpha)^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \alpha^{d}}}-\frac{1}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2}}\right|
$$

and then for $\alpha \in[0,1]$,

$$
\left|\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} \alpha} h(y, \alpha)\right|=\frac{1}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d}}\left|-d \frac{1}{\alpha^{d+1}} e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \alpha^{d}}}+\frac{1}{\alpha^{d}} e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \alpha^{d}}} \cdot \frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{\alpha^{3}}\right| \leq \frac{e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2 \alpha^{d}}}}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d} \alpha^{d+3}} \cdot|d+\|y\|_{2}{ }^{2} \mid
$$

Because $h(y, 1)=0$, we see that (36) is bounded by

$$
\frac{\left(1-\sigma_{t}\right)}{\sigma_{t}{ }^{d+3}} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \frac{e^{-\frac{\|y\|_{2}^{2}}{2}}}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d}} \cdot|d+\|y\|_{2}{ }^{2}|\mathrm{~d} y=\frac{2 d\left(1-\sigma_{t}\right)}{\sigma_{t}{ }^{d+3}}
$$

which goes to 0 exponentially as $t \rightarrow+\infty$ because $\sigma_{t}=\sqrt{1-e^{-2 t}}$. The estimates (35) and (37) together give (30). Next we show (31). There are two cases: if $e^{-t} \sqrt{d} D \geq 1$, then (31) holds trivially, since the lefthand side is at most 2 . Otherwise $e^{-t} \sqrt{d} D \leq 1$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{2 d\left(1-\sigma_{t}\right)}{\sigma_{t}{ }^{d+3}}+\lambda_{t} \sqrt{d} D \frac{4+\lambda_{t} \sqrt{d} D}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \cdot e^{\frac{\lambda_{t}^{2} d D^{2}}{2 \sigma_{t}{ }^{2}}} \leq \frac{2 d e^{-2 t}}{\sigma_{t}^{2 d}}+\frac{4 e^{-t} \sqrt{d} D+\left(e^{-t} \sqrt{d} D\right)^{2}}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \cdot e^{\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{t}{ }^{2}}} \\
\leq & \frac{2 d e^{-2 t}}{\sigma_{t}^{2 d}}+\frac{5 e^{-t} \sqrt{d} D}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} e^{\frac{2}{3}}=\frac{2 d e^{-2 t}}{\left(1-e^{-2 t}\right)^{d}}+\frac{5 e^{-t} \sqrt{d} D}{1-e^{-2 t}} e^{\frac{2}{3}} \\
\leq & \frac{2 \sqrt{d} e^{-t}}{1-d e^{-2 t}} \cdot \sqrt{d} e^{-t}+\frac{5 e^{-t} \sqrt{d} D}{1-e^{-2 t}} e^{\frac{2}{3}} \leq C_{u} e^{-t} \sqrt{d} D
\end{aligned}
$$

for a universal constant $C_{u}>0$. In the last inequality, we assume that $e^{-t} \leq \frac{1}{4 \sqrt{d}} \leq \frac{1}{4}$. Otherwise, if $e^{-t} \geq \frac{1}{4 \sqrt{d}}$, (31) also holds trivially. This finishes the proof of (31).

When we prove our main theorem, Theorem 3.5, in the following Section C, we will assume that $\mu_{*}$ has a compact support $K_{*}$ and use Lemma B. 3 to complete the proof. On the other hand, as we have mentioned in Remark 3.6, our methods work under other assumptions on the initial data $\mu_{*}$, as long as under those assumptions, we can reasonably obtain the properties in Remark C.4. We next assume that $\mu_{*}$ is a Gaussian mixture and obtain an estimate similar to Lemma B.3.

Lemma B.5. Assume that $\mu_{*}$ is a Gaussian mixture, i.e., we assume that

$$
\mu_{*}(x):=\sum_{k=1}^{M} c_{k} \frac{1}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d} a_{k}} \cdot \exp \left(-\frac{1}{2}\left(x-b_{k}\right) \cdot A_{k}^{-1}\left(x-b_{k}\right)\right)
$$

where $A_{k}$ 's are positive definite matrices, $a_{k}:=\sqrt{\operatorname{det} A_{k}}, b_{k}$ 's are constant vectors in $\mathbb{R}^{d}, c_{k}>0$ and $\sum_{k=1}^{M} c_{k}=1$. Then, for any $\ell \in \mathbb{Z}_{+}$and any multi-index $\alpha$ with $|\alpha| \leq \ell$, there is a constant $C\left(\ell, \mu_{*}\right)$, depending on $\ell$ and $A_{k}, b_{k}$ in the formula of $\mu_{*}$, such that for any $x \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ and any $t \geq 0$,

$$
\frac{\left|\partial_{s}^{\alpha} q_{t}(x)\right|}{q_{t}(x)} \leq C\left(\ell, \mu_{*}\right) \cdot\|x\|_{2}^{\ell}+C\left(\ell, \mu_{*}\right)
$$

Proof. A standard computation, by (23), shows that the density function of $q_{t}(x)$ is

$$
q_{t}(x):=\sum_{k=1}^{M} c_{k} \frac{1}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d} \cdot a_{k}(t)} \cdot \exp \left(-\frac{1}{2}\left(x-b_{k}(t)\right) \cdot A_{k}(t)^{-1}\left(x-b_{k}(t)\right)\right)
$$

where $A_{k}(t)=\lambda_{t}^{2} A_{k}+\sigma_{t}^{2} \mathbb{I}_{d}, b_{k}(t)=\lambda_{t} b_{k}$. Hence,

$$
\nabla q_{t}(x)=\sum_{k=1}^{M} c_{k} \frac{-A_{k}(t)^{-1}\left(x-b_{k}(t)\right)}{(\sqrt{2 \pi})^{d} \cdot a_{k}(t)} \cdot \exp \left(-\frac{1}{2}\left(x-b_{k}(t)\right) \cdot A_{k}(t)^{-1}\left(x-b_{k}(t)\right)\right)
$$

So,

$$
\left|\partial_{1} q_{t}(x)\right| \leq \max _{1 \leq k \leq M}\left\|-A_{k}(t)^{-1}\left(x-b_{k}(t)\right)\right\| \cdot q_{t}(x)
$$

Notice that because when $t=0, A_{k}$ 's are positive definite, and when $t \rightarrow+\infty, A_{k}(t) \rightarrow \mathbb{I}_{d}$, there is an upper bound $C\left(\ell, \mu_{*}\right)$, such that $\sup _{t \in[0,+\infty)}\left\|A_{k}(t)^{-1}\right\| \leq C\left(\ell, \mu_{*}\right)$. Hence, we can obtain (38) for $\ell=1$. For general $\ell \geq 1$, one can either use induction or compute them directly, exactly using the same way as the case $\ell=1$ we have shown. For the purpose of proving Theorem 3.5, the estimates for $\ell \leq 3$ will be enough.

Next, we also point out that those $\widehat{q}_{t}$ 's also have exponential tails, as long as one of them has an exponential tail at a given time. For example, if $\widehat{q}_{T}=q_{T}$.
Lemma B.6. If for a $t^{\prime}>0, \widehat{q}_{t^{\prime}}(x)$ has an exponential tail as $\|x\|_{2} \rightarrow+\infty$, then for any $t>0$, $\widehat{q}_{t}(x)$ also has an exponential tail as $\|x\|_{2} \rightarrow+\infty$.
Proof. Notice that $\partial_{t} \widehat{q}_{t}=\nabla \cdot\left(\widehat{U}_{t} \widehat{q}_{t}\right)$. Hence, along the characteristic line $\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d} t} T_{t}(x)=-\widehat{U}_{t^{\prime}+t}\left(T_{t}(x)\right)$, one can solve that

$$
\widehat{q}_{t^{\prime}+t}\left(T_{t}(x)\right)=\widehat{q}_{t^{\prime}}(x) \cdot \exp \left(\int_{0}^{t}\left(\nabla \cdot \widehat{U}_{t^{\prime}+s}\right)\left(T_{s}(x)\right) \mathrm{d} s\right)
$$

Because $\widehat{U}_{t}(x)=x+s_{T-t}(x)$, by Assumption 3.3, we have that $\left|\left(\nabla \cdot \widehat{U}_{t}\right)(x)\right| \leq d\left(1+L_{T-t}\right)$ for any $t>0$. The remaining estimate is on the norm of $T_{t}(x)$. We notice that, by Assumption 3.3 again,

$$
\left\|s_{T-t}(x)\right\|_{2} \leq\left\|s_{T-t}(0)\right\|_{2}+\left(\|x\|_{2} \cdot d \cdot L_{T-t}\right) \leq d \cdot L_{T-t}(1+\|x\|_{2})
$$

Hence,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|\partial_{t}\right\| T_{t}(x)\left\|_{2}^{2}\right|=\left|\widehat{U}_{t^{\prime}+t}\left(T_{t}(x)\right) \cdot T_{t}(x)\right| & \leq\left(1+d L_{T-t^{\prime}-t}\right)\left\|T_{t}(x)\right\|_{2}^{2}+d L_{T-t^{\prime}-t}\left\|T_{t}(x)\right\|_{2} \\
& \leq\left(2+d L_{T-t^{\prime}-t}\right)\left\|T_{t}(x)\right\|_{2}^{2}+d^{2} L_{T-t^{\prime}-t}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Denote $\mathcal{L}_{t}=\int_{0}^{t}\left(2+d \cdot L_{T-t^{\prime}-s}\right) \mathrm{d} s$. Hence, for $t>0$,

$$

$$

Because we can compare the norms of $T_{t}(x)$ and $x$ by a factor only depending on $t$, and $T_{t}$ is also a diffeomorphism since $\widehat{U}_{t}(x)$ is locally Lipschitz, then we know that $\widehat{q}_{t}(x)$ also has an exponential tail as $\|x\|_{2} \rightarrow+\infty$. One can obtain a similar result for $t<0$.

For the convenience of readers, let us also sketch the proof of this inequality here.

Lemma C. 1 (Gagliardo-Nirenberg). There is a positive universal constant $C_{u}$, such that for any $d \in \mathbb{Z}_{+}$, any $w \in L^{1}$, any $i \in \llbracket 1, d \rrbracket$, if $\partial_{i i}^{2} w \in L^{1}$, then

$$
\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\partial_{i} w(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x\right)^{2} \leq C_{u}\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\partial_{i i}^{2} w(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x\right)\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}|w(x)| \mathrm{d} x\right)
$$

In general, if $\partial_{i}^{k} w \in L^{1}$ with $k \geq 2$, then

$$
\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\partial_{i} w(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x \leq C_{u}^{\frac{k-1}{2}}\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\partial_{i}^{k} w(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x\right)^{\frac{1}{k}}\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}|w(x)| \mathrm{d} x\right)^{\frac{k-1}{k}}
$$

$$
\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}}\left|\partial_{1} w\left(x_{1}, x^{\prime}\right)\right| \mathrm{d} x_{1}\right)^{2} \leq C_{u}\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}}\left|\partial_{11}^{2} w\left(x_{1}, x^{\prime}\right)\right| \mathrm{d} x_{1}\right)\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}}\left|w\left(x_{1}, x^{\prime}\right)\right| \mathrm{d} x_{1}\right)

Hence,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\partial_{i} w(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x\right) & =\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d-1}} \int_{\mathbb{R}}\left|\partial_{1} w\left(x_{1}, x^{\prime}\right)\right| \mathrm{d} x_{1} \mathrm{~d} x^{\prime}\right) \\
& \leq C_{u}^{\frac{1}{2}} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d-1}}\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}}\left|\partial_{11}^{2} w\left(x_{1}, x^{\prime}\right)\right| \mathrm{d} x_{1}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}}\left|w\left(x_{1}, x^{\prime}\right)\right| \mathrm{d} x_{1}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}} \mathrm{~d} x^{\prime} \\

\end{aligned}
$$

In general, assume that we already know that for some $k \geq 2$,

$$
\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\partial_{i} w(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x \leq C_{u}^{\frac{k-1}{2}}\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}\left|\partial_{i}^{k} w(x)\right| \mathrm{d} x\right)^{\frac{1}{k}}\left(\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}}|w(x)| \mathrm{d} x\right)^{\frac{k-1}{k}}

then we replace $w(x)$ with $\partial_{i} w(x)$, and obtain that

$$

As discussed in Section 2.2, we solve the ODE flow $\partial_{t} \widehat{Y}_{t}=\widehat{Y}_{t}+s_{t}\left(\widehat{Y}_{t}\right)=\widehat{V}_{t}\left(\widehat{Y}_{t}\right)$ using the RungeKutta method. Although the Runge-Kutta updating rule as in (7) is a discrete time process, we can interpolate it as a continuous time process on $t_{i} \leq t \leq t_{i+1}$ as

$$
\widehat{Y}_{t}=F_{r}\left(\widehat{Y}_{t_{i}}\right), \quad t=t_{i}+r
$$

where

$$
F_{r}(x)=x+r \sum_{j=1}^{s} b_{j} k_{j}, \quad 0 \leq r \leq t_{i+1}-t_{i}=h
$$

and

$$
\begin{aligned}
& k_{1}(x)=\widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r c_{1}}(x) \\
& k_{2}(x)=\widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r c_{2}}\left(x+r\left(a_{21} k_{1}\right)\right) \\

$$

$$

where again we used that $8 s L B r d \leq 1$.

$$

\end{aligned}

where we used that $8 s L B r d \leq 1$. We denote the functional inverse of $F_{r}$ as $F_{r}^{-1}(x)$, then (49) follows from (47).

Next we show the claim (50) follows from the following statement: for $0 \leq r \leq t_{i+1}-t_{i} \leq h$

$$

where in the third line we used that $8 r s B L d \leq 8 h s B L d \leq 1$ and (69).

$$
\sum_{1 \leq i \leq j-1} r^{\zeta} a_{j i} \partial_{r}^{\beta-\alpha} \nabla^{\alpha+1} \widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r c_{j}}\left[k_{i}, u_{1}, u_{2}, \cdots, u_{\alpha}\right]
$$

where each summand is in $\mathcal{D}_{m+1}$, with the parameters (78) given by $\left(m_{1}^{\prime}, m_{2}^{\prime}, m_{3}^{\prime}, m_{4}^{\prime}, m_{5}^{\prime}, m_{6}^{\prime}\right)=$ $\left(m_{1}, m_{2}, m_{3}+1, m_{4}, m_{5}, m_{6}\right)$.
(4) If $\partial_{r}$ hits $k_{i}$ in $\left(x+r\left(a_{j 1} k_{1}+a_{j 2} k_{2}+\cdots+a_{j j-1} k_{j-1}\right)\right.$ for some $1 \leq i \leq j-1$, we get

$$
r^{\zeta+1} \partial_{r}^{\beta-\alpha} \nabla^{\alpha+1} \widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r c_{j}}\left[\partial_{r} k_{i}, u_{1}, u_{2}, \cdots, u_{\alpha}\right] \in \mathcal{D}_{m+1}
$$

with the parameters (78) given by $\left(m_{1}^{\prime}, m_{2}^{\prime}, m_{3}^{\prime}, m_{4}^{\prime}, m_{5}^{\prime}, m_{6}^{\prime}\right)=\left(m_{1}, m_{2}, m_{3}, m_{4}+1, m_{5}, m_{6}\right)$.
(5) If $\partial_{r}$ hits $u_{\gamma}$ and $u_{\gamma}=k_{i}$ we get

$$
\partial_{r}^{\beta-\alpha} \nabla^{\alpha} \widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r c_{j}}\left[u_{1}, u_{2}, \cdots, u_{\gamma-1}, \partial_{r} k_{i}, u_{\gamma+1}, \cdots, u_{\alpha}\right] \in \mathcal{D}_{m+1}
$$

with the parameters (78) given by $\left(m_{1}^{\prime}, m_{2}^{\prime}, m_{3}^{\prime}, m_{4}^{\prime}, m_{5}^{\prime}, m_{6}^{\prime}\right)=\left(m_{1}, m_{2}, m_{3}, m_{4}, m_{5}+1, m_{6}\right)$.
(6) If $\partial_{r}$ hits $u_{\gamma}$ and $u_{\gamma}=\partial_{r}^{\ell_{\gamma}} k_{i}$ with $\ell_{\gamma} \geq 1$ we get

$$
\partial_{r}^{\beta-\alpha} \nabla^{\alpha} \widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r c_{j}}\left[u_{1}, u_{2}, \cdots, u_{\gamma-1}, \partial_{r}^{\ell_{\gamma}+1} k_{i}, u_{\gamma+1}, \cdots, u_{\alpha}\right] \in \mathcal{D}_{m+1}
$$

with the parameters (78) given by $\left(m_{1}^{\prime}, m_{2}^{\prime}, m_{3}^{\prime}, m_{4}^{\prime}, m_{5}^{\prime}, m_{6}^{\prime}\right)=\left(m_{1}, m_{2}, m_{3}, m_{4}, m_{5}, m_{6}+1\right)$.

We conclude that for $v \in \mathcal{D}_{m}, \partial_{r} v$ is a linear combination of finite terms in $\mathcal{D}_{m+1}$. In particular, $\partial_{r}^{m} k_{j}$ is a linear combination of at most $(2+2 s+p)^{p}$ terms in $\mathcal{D}_{m}$, with coefficients bounded by $\max \{p, B\}^{p}$

In the following, we show the following bound for vectors in $v \in \mathcal{D}_{m}$

$$
\|v\|_{\infty} \lesssim L\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m}, \quad m \geq 1
$$

Then it follows

$$
\left\|\partial_{r}^{m} k_{j}\right\|_{\infty} \lesssim L\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m}
$$

and the first statement in (75) holds.
We prove (79) by induction. We recall that $\left\|k_{i}\right\|_{2} \leq 2 L\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right)$ from Lemma D.2. It follows that $\left\|k_{i}\right\|_{1} \leq 2 \sqrt{d} L\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right)$. We assume (79) holds for $1,2, \cdots, m-1$, and next we prove it for $m$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left\|r^{\zeta} \partial_{r}^{\beta-\alpha} \nabla^{\alpha} \widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r c_{j}}\left[u_{1}, u_{2}, \cdots, u_{\alpha}\right]\right\|_{\infty} \leq r^{\zeta}\left\|\partial_{r}^{\beta-\alpha} \nabla^{\alpha} \widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r c_{j}}\right\|_{\infty}\left\|u_{1}\right\|_{1}\left\|u_{2}\right\|_{1} \cdots\left\|u_{\alpha}\right\|_{1} \\
& \lesssim L r^{\zeta} \prod_{\gamma: \ell_{\gamma}=0}\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right) \prod_{\gamma: \ell_{\gamma} \geq 1} d L\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{\ell_{\gamma}} \\
& =L r^{\zeta}\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{\alpha} \prod_{\gamma: \ell_{\gamma} \geq 1} d L\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{\ell_{\gamma}-1} \\
& =L r^{m_{4}-m_{1}}\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m_{3}+m_{4}}(d L)^{m_{4}+m_{5}}\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m_{6}} \\
& =L(r d L)^{m_{4}-m_{1}}\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m_{3}+m_{4}}(d L)^{m_{1}+m_{5}}\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m_{6}} \\
& \lesssim L(r d L)^{m_{4}-m_{1}}\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m}
\end{aligned}
$$

where in the last line we used (78) and $d L \leq\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L$. By our assumption, $r \sqrt{d} L \leq 1$ and $m_{4}-m_{1} \geq 0$. This finishes the proof of (79).

In the following, we prove the second statement in (75). We define the following set of $d \times d$ matrices $\widetilde{\mathcal{D}}_{0}, \widetilde{\mathcal{D}}_{1}, \widetilde{\mathcal{D}}_{2}, \cdots$. Let $\widetilde{\mathcal{D}}_{0}=\left\{\nabla k_{1}, \nabla k_{2}, \cdots, \nabla k_{j}\right\}$. Then thanks to Lemma D.2, for any $v \in \widetilde{\mathcal{D}}_{0}$,

$$
\|v\|_{\infty} \leq 2 L
$$

We denote $\widetilde{\mathcal{D}}_{m}$ the set of matrices obtained from taking gradient of (77), with respect to $x$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& r^{\zeta} \partial_{r}^{\beta-\alpha} \nabla^{\alpha+1} \widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r c_{j}}\left[\left(\mathbb{I}_{d}+r\left(a_{j 1} \nabla k_{1}+a_{j 2} \nabla k_{2}+\cdots+a_{j j-1} \nabla k_{j-1}\right)\right), u_{1}, u_{2}, \cdots, u_{\alpha}\right] \\
& r^{\zeta} \partial_{r}^{\beta-\alpha} \nabla^{\alpha} \widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r c_{j}}\left[u_{1}, u_{2}, \cdots, u_{\gamma-1}, \nabla u_{\gamma}, u_{\gamma+1}, \cdots, u_{\alpha}\right], \quad 1 \leq \gamma \leq \alpha
\end{aligned}
$$

Then $\partial_{r}^{m} \nabla k_{j}$ is a finite linear combination of terms in $\widetilde{\mathcal{D}}_{m}$.
Next we show by induction that $v \in \mathcal{D}_{m}$,

$$
\|v\|_{\infty} \lesssim L\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m}, \quad m \geq 1
$$

Then it follows

$$
\left\|\partial_{r}^{m} \nabla k_{j}\right\|_{\infty} \lesssim L\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m}
$$

and the second statement in (75) holds.
Similarly to (80), we can bound the $L^{\infty}$-norm of $v$ as

$$
\begin{aligned}
L r^{\zeta}(1+2 s B r L)\left\|u_{1}\right\|_{1}\left\|u_{2}\right\|_{1} \cdots\left\|u_{\alpha}\right\|_{1} & \leq 2 L r^{\zeta}\left\|u_{1}\right\|_{1}\left\|u_{2}\right\|_{1} \cdots\left\|u_{\alpha}\right\|_{1} \\
& \lesssim 2 L\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m}
\end{aligned}
$$

Also, for any $q \in\{1,2, \ldots, d\}$, we can similarly obtain that

$$
\begin{aligned}
L r^{\zeta}\left\|\partial_{q} u_{\gamma}\right\|_{1} \prod_{\gamma^{\prime} \neq \gamma}\left\|u_{\gamma^{\prime}}\right\|_{1} & \lesssim L r^{\zeta} d L\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{\ell_{\gamma}} \prod_{\gamma^{\prime} \neq \gamma}\left\|u_{\gamma^{\prime}}\right\|_{1} \\
& \lesssim 2 L\left(2\left(\sqrt{d}+\|x\|_{2}\right) \sqrt{d} L\right)^{m}
\end{aligned}
$$

as we did in (80). This gives (83).

$$
\widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r}\left(F_{r}\right)=\widehat{V}_{t_{i}+r}\left(x+r \sum_{j=1}^{s} b_{j} k_{j}\right)
$$

abstract:
Score-based generative models have emerged as a powerful approach for
sampling high-dimensional probability distributions. Despite their
effectiveness, their theoretical underpinnings remain relatively
underdeveloped. In this work, we study the convergence properties of
deterministic samplers based on probability flow ODEs from both theoretical and
numerical perspectives. Assuming access to $L^2$-accurate estimates of the
score function, we prove the total variation between the target and the
generated data distributions can be bounded above by
$\mathcal{O}(d^{3/4}\delta^{1/2})$ in the continuous time level, where $d$
denotes the data dimension and $\delta$ represents the $L^2$-score matching
error. For practical implementations using a $p$-th order Runge-Kutta
integrator with step size $h$, we establish error bounds of
$\mathcal{O}(d^{3/4}\delta^{1/2} + d\cdot(dh)^p)$ at the discrete level.
Finally, we present numerical studies on problems up to 128 dimensions to
verify our theory.
